{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510327"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:27:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:27:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11524"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11524"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.68,0.02,0.06,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43629"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4155"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11524"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28640"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9196"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5326"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43869"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43629"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-week history of abdominal cramps and faecal urgency. He has noticed blood in his stools, and often experiences pain in his lower left abdomen when defaecating. He has been passing about six bowel actions a day. He has been feeling fatigued lately but reports no weight loss. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft to palpation and there are no abnormal findings. Digital rectal examination finds soft, blood-stained stool. The patient has been assessed with an endoscopy, colonoscopy and MRI small bowel. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely finding to support the working diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Skip lesions in the terminal ileum","Confluent mucosal surface ulceration with loss of vascular pattern and friability","Evidence of fistulisation","Histological findings showing villous atrophy and crypt hyperplasia in the duodenum","Deep serpentine ulceration with areas of mucosal sparing"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms are very suggestive of inflammatory bowel disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConfluent mucosal surface ulceration with loss of vascular pattern and friability\u003C/strong\u003E, along with crypt abscesses and loss of haustra (i.e. lead-pipe sign), are all typical colonoscopic findings in ulcerative colitis (UC). This is the primarily differential diagnosis as this man presents with typical features of the disease. Abdominal cramps, hematochezia, faecal urgency and painful defecation (felt in the LLQ) are characteristic of UC. Due to the chronic blood loss and subsequent anaemia, it is common for patients with an active flare to feel fatigued. The Mayo Score is a tool that can be used to assess severity of disease in UC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkip lesions in the terminal ileum\u003C/strong\u003E and creeping fat are characteristic findings of Crohn\u0027s disease, the other most common inflammatory bowel disease. \u003Cstrong\u003EDeep serpentine ulceration with areas of mucosal sparing \u003C/strong\u003Eis also a typical finding in this disease. \u003Cstrong\u003EEvidence of fistulisation \u003C/strong\u003Ewould also be more commonly seen in Crohn\u0027s disease due to the presence of transmural inflammation. When considering signs and symptoms, Crohn\u0027s disease typically has non-bloody diarrhoea and signs of malnutrition, compared to ulcerative colitis. The SES-CD score is a tool that can be used to assess severity of disease in Crohn\u0027s disease, based on endoscopy findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistological findings showing villous atrophy and crypt hyperplasia in the duodenum \u003C/strong\u003Eare characteristic findings in coeliac disease, which is due to a maladaptive immune response to gluten. Symptoms of malabsorption would be characteristic in such a condition e.g. steatorrhoea, flatulence, bloating and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ulcerative colitis generally presents clinically with abdominal cramps, fecal urgency and bloody stools","Friable mucosa, crypt abscesses, loss of haustra and continuous mucosal ulcerations are classical findings in ulcerative colitis","Villous atrophy and crypt hyperplasia in the duodenum is seen in Coeliac disease","Skip lesions and creeping fat and characteristic of Crohn\u0027s disease"],"references":["Roy MA, Rutgeerts P, Saltzman JR, Robson KM. Endoscopic Diagnosis of Inflammatory Bowel Disease. In: UpToDate [online]. 2016. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/endoscopic-diagnosis-of-inflammatory-bowel-disease.","Zimmerman J, Gavish D, Rachmilewitz D. Early and late onset ulcerative colitis: distinct clinical features. J Clin Gastroenterol. 1985;7(6):492-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/4086743/","Oxentenko AS, Rubio-Tapia A. Celiac Disease. Mayo Clinic Proceedings. 2019;94(12):2556-71. Available at: https://www.mayoclinicproceedings.org/article/S0025-6196(19)30266-6/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28640"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11524"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28640"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-24T21:20:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-24T21:20:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4155"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43629"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},